'''Dr. Ulrich Cartellieri''' (born 21 September 1937) is a German businessman, a [[non-executive director]] of [[BAE Systems]] from 1999 to 2007, a member of the Supervisory Board of [[Robert Bosch GmbH]] and a member of the International Advisory Committee of the [[Federal Reserve Bank]] of New York.<ref name="BAEbio">{{cite web| url = http://www.baesystems.com/aboutus/cartellieri.htm| title = About Us: Leadership Biographies | accessdate = 2007-01-01| date = | work = www.baesystems.com| publisher = [[BAE Systems]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061217210715/http://www.baesystems.com/aboutus/cartellieri.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-17}}</ref>

On 28 October 2004, Cartellieri resigned from the board of [[Deutsche Bank]] because he could "no longer support" the leadership of CEO [[Josef Ackermann]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Gail| last = Edmondson | title = Has Deutsche Bank Lost Its Way?; Having failed to find a merger partner, Ackermann plans a radical makeover. Investors are skeptical | work = Business Week | publisher = The McGraw-Hill Companies | page = 140 | date = 2004-11-22 }}</ref> He has also served on the boards of [[KarstadtQuelle|Karstadt AG]] (Chairman), [[Siemens AG]] (Deputy Chairman), [[ThyssenKrupp]] and [[Henkel|Henkel KGaA]], and [[German Investment Corporation|DEG]].<ref name="BAEbio"/>

